1. **Notification to the California Attorney General**: The California Attorney General must be notified within 72 hours of discovering a data breach that affects 500 or more California residents [10].
2. **Notification to the affected individuals**: The breached entity must notify the affected individuals within 60 days of discovering the breach [4].
3. **Content of the notification**: The notification must include the following information:
	* A description of the breach, including the date of the breach and the date of discovery;
	* The types of personal information that were involved in the breach;
	* A description of the steps the breached entity is taking to investigate the breach, to contain and remediate the breach, and to protect the affected individuals' personal information;
	* A description of the steps the breached entity is taking to protect against future breaches;
	* A toll-free telephone number and an email address that the affected individuals can use to contact the breached entity to ask questions about the breach;
	* A statement that the breached entity will provide the affected individuals with a copy of the notice free of charge;
	* A statement that the breached entity will provide the affected individuals with a copy of the notice in the form of a clear and conspicuous written notice;
	* A statement that the breached entity will provide the affected individuals with a copy of the notice in the form of a clear and conspicuous electronic notice;
	* A statement that the breached entity will provide the affected individuals with a copy of the notice in the form of a clear and conspicuous written notice that is mailed to the affected individuals at their last known address; and
	* A statement that the breached entity will provide the affected individuals with a copy of the notice in the form of a clear and conspicuous electronic notice that is sent to the affected individuals at their last known email address [4].
